<h2 id="the-history-of-">The History of ã‚ãªãŸ</h2>

<p>Before getting into all the nuances, let me walk you through a brief history of ã‚ãªãŸ. It explains a lot about why some say ã‚ãªãŸ is rude and some say it's polite.</p>

<p>The word was initially used to refer to a thing or a place that was far away. Because Japanese culture tends to avoid directness, people started to use ã‚ãªãŸ to refer to a person in an indirect and polite way. It eventually became a way to address someone, and acquired the meaning "you." At first, it was a polite word used only for people of higher social status. Later, as part of the drive to standardize the Japanese language, which happened during the Meiji and Showa periods, language guidelines encouraged citizens to use ã‚ãªãŸ as the standard second-person pronoun.</p>

<p>Over time, the initial honorific connotations of ã‚ãªãŸ changed. Nowadays, it can even come off as impolite. In fact, this happened not only to ã‚ãªãŸ, but also to all the other Japanese second-person pronouns. <i></i> <ruby>è²´æ§˜<rp>ï¼ˆ</rp><rt>ãã•ã¾</rt><rp>ï¼‰</rp></ruby> is a good example of this phenomenon. It's a second-person pronoun that's derogatory and clearly very rude these days. However, the kanji components è²´ (noble) and æ§˜ (honorific title/name ender) show that it was once a very polite term.</p>

<blockquote class="highlight-right">
  <p>Over time, the initial honorific connotations of ã‚ãªãŸ changed. Nowadays, it can even come off as impolite.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>This common tendency of words losing politeness over time is inevitable due to the nature of second-person pronouns in Japanese. Once a word starts being used as a second-person pronoun, it gradually acquires a feeling of "directness," which is considered impolite in Japanese. ã‚ãªãŸ is not yet as unequivocally offensive as some of the other second-person pronouns, but it's definitely following the same path.</p>

<h2 id="what-does--sound-like-these-days">What Does ã‚ãªãŸ Sound Like These Days?</h2>

<figure class="figure-middle"><img alt="a blank canvas with coloring supplies around" src="https://files.tofugu.com/articles/japanese/2021-01-19-anata/blank-canvas.jpg" /></figure>

<p>Since the connotation that ã‚ãªãŸ carries has shifted so much over time, what does that mean for its usage today? Does it still carry some of the polite underpinnings of its past, or is it overly direct and rude? As is often the case with language, we can't make a blanket statement that covers all cases â€” everything comes down to context.</p>

<p>So, rather than fretting about whether ã‚ãªãŸ is polite or rude, it's best to think of it as a blank canvas. On its own, it's the most plain and neutral second-person pronoun. Then, depending on how it's used, it takes on different connotations. According to the relationship between the speaker and listener, the attitude of the speaker, and whether it's used in written or verbal communication, ã‚ãªãŸ can sound condescending, respectful, or even affectionate.</p>

<p>This is pretty unique amongst second-person pronouns. Other options like <a href="../japanese-grammar/second-person-pronouns.1#section-1"><i></i> <ruby>å›<rp>ï¼ˆ</rp><rt>ãã¿</rt><rp>ï¼‰</rp></ruby></a> and <a href="../japanese-grammar/second-person-pronouns.1#section-2"><i></i> <ruby>ãŠå‰<rp>ï¼ˆ</rp><rt>ã€€ã¾ãˆ</rt><rp>ï¼‰</rp></ruby></a> almost always suggest that the speaker believes they hold a higher social status than the addressee, or at least, they're equal. They often give the impression that the speaker is looking down on the addressee as well. ã‚ãªãŸ could create a similar effect, but that's not always the case. To really see how ã‚ãªãŸ sounds today, we need to look at it in a variety of different contexts.</p>

<h2 id="when--is-neutral">When ã‚ãªãŸ is Neutral</h2>

