<h2 id="when--is-not-neutral">When ã‚ãªãŸ Is NOT Neutral</h2>

<p>So far, we've discussed how ã‚ãªãŸ is used neutrally. Now, let's talk about how it can take on different colors andÂ nuances.</p>

<p>When someone uses ã‚ãªãŸ to address or refer to you in person, it tends to express a particular nuance. That's because it's a choice that's made over the other more common options â€” omitting the second-person pronoun or calling someone by their name, family role, or social role. Thus, it could be taken as either rude or polite.</p>

