<p>You'll be able to spot ã‚ãªãŸ used like this in shows, such as with stereotypical "perfect wife" figures in the olden days, or else in cheesy interactions of lovey-dovey couples. However, the usage is actually quite rare in today's real-life speech. Many studies show there are few people who actually call their husbands ã‚ãªãŸ nowadays. If used in daily conversation today, it's likely by someone from an older generation.</p>

<p>We should also point out that husbands can technically use ã‚ãªãŸ for their wives too. If a husband uses ã‚ãªãŸ to address his wife, though, the nuance could be rather condescending, as opposed to affectionate.</p>

<h3 id="for-putting-on-a-calm-front">ã‚ãªãŸ for Putting on a Calm Front</h3>

<figure class="figure-middle"><img alt="an angry person with a mask of a calm face" src="https://files.tofugu.com/articles/japanese/2021-01-19-anata/angry-anata.jpg" /></figure>

<p>There is some truth to how people say ã‚ãªãŸ is rude, especially in face-to-face conversation. Instead of calling a person by their name or their family/social role ("mom" or "doctor," for example), which feels more personal and friendly, using ã‚ãªãŸ can come off as patronizing or standoffish.</p>

<p>Since ã‚ãªãŸ is still a somewhat formal-sounding word, it is not as <em>obviously</em> rude as derogatory pronouns like ãŠå‰, or the very casual version of ã‚ãªãŸ â€” ã‚ã‚“ãŸ. You can use ã‚ãªãŸ as a formality to sound rational and professional when you communicate negative emotions, such as anger, hatred, hostility, or a sense of rivalry. Basically, you're pretending to be polite, and that's just to present yourself as calm and collected. And this often results in sounding condescending. It's such a roundabout, passive-aggressive style, but it could be an effective way to express these negative emotions.</p>

<p>To use an example, let's say your mom is upset because you forgot to lock the door. She might say:</p>

